##  The Architecture: How We Built the Prediction System

Our prediction system is built as a pipeline with five distinct stages, where each stage processes the output of the previous stage. This modular design makes the system easier to understand, debug, and improve. Let me walk you through each stage in detail.

The first stage is data exploration and understanding. Before building any model, we need to deeply understand our data. We loaded the training sequences and examined their properties - how long are typical proteins, what amino acids are common, are there any unusual patterns? We analyzed the annotation data to understand the distribution of GO terms - which functions are common, which are rare, how many functions does each protein typically have? We also examined the Gene Ontology structure itself to understand the relationships between terms. This exploratory phase is crucial because it informs all our later decisions about model architecture, training parameters, and evaluation strategies.

The second stage is feature extraction using ESM2. This is where we convert raw protein sequences into numerical representations that machine learning models can work with. For each protein in both our training and test sets, we feed its amino acid sequence into the pre-trained ESM2 model. The model processes the sequence through its 33 transformer layers, with each layer building increasingly sophisticated representations of the sequence. At the final layer, we take the embeddings from all positions in the sequence and average them together to get a single 1,280-dimensional vector representing the entire protein. This process is computationally intensive - it took about 40 minutes to process all 82,000 training proteins using a GPU, and each protein requires about 2-3 seconds of computation. The resulting embeddings are saved to disk as pickle files, which are Python's way of serializing data structures for later use.

The third stage is label preparation, which turns out to be more complex than you might initially think. We start with raw annotation data that lists which GO terms are associated with which proteins. The first challenge is that there are over 26,000 different GO terms in our training data, but many of these are extremely rare - some appear on only 1 or 2 proteins. Training models to predict all 26,000 terms would be impractical and ineffective, so we need to select a subset of the most important terms. We do this separately for each ontology, selecting the top 500 most frequent Molecular Function terms, 800 Biological Process terms, and 400 Cellular Component terms. This gives us 1,700 terms total to predict, which balances coverage (predicting many useful functions) with tractability (having enough training examples per term).

But selecting terms is just the first part of label preparation. We also need to handle the GO hierarchy. When a protein is annotated with a specific term, it should also be annotated with all parent terms in the hierarchy. This is called "propagation" - we propagate annotations up the tree. For example, if a protein is annotated with "serine/threonine kinase activity," we also need to add annotations for "protein kinase activity," "kinase activity," "phosphotransferase activity," and so on up to the root "molecular function" term. This ensures our training labels are consistent with the biological meaning of the ontology. After propagation, we create binary label matrices - for each protein and each GO term, we have a 1 if the protein has that function and 0 if it doesn't. This gives us three large matrices: one for Molecular Function (82,404 proteins × 500 terms), one for Biological Process (82,404 × 800), and one for Cellular Component (82,404 × 400).

The fourth stage is model training, where the machine learning actually happens. We decided to train three separate neural networks - one for each ontology. This is called a "one-vs-all" or "binary relevance" approach to multi-label classification. Each network takes a protein embedding as input (those 1,280 numbers from ESM2) and outputs probabilities for all GO terms in that ontology. The network architecture consists of multiple layers. The first hidden layer has 512 neurons and learns to combine and transform the input features in useful ways. After this layer, we apply a ReLU activation function (which introduces non-linearity, allowing the network to learn complex patterns), batch normalization (which stabilizes training), and dropout (which randomly turns off 30% of neurons during training to prevent overfitting). We then have a second hidden layer with 256 neurons, followed again by activation, normalization, and dropout. Finally, the output layer has one neuron for each GO term we're predicting, and we apply a sigmoid activation function to convert the network's raw outputs into probabilities between 0 and 1.

Training a neural network means finding the right values for all its parameters (the weights and biases in each layer) so that it makes good predictions. We do this through a process called backpropagation with gradient descent. For each batch of proteins in our training set, we feed their embeddings through the network to get predicted probabilities, compare these predictions to the true labels using a loss function (binary cross-entropy, which measures how different the predictions are from the truth), and then calculate how to adjust each parameter to reduce this loss. We use the Adam optimizer, which is a sophisticated version of gradient descent that adapts the learning rate for each parameter. We train for 20 epochs, where an epoch means going through the entire training dataset once. During training, we monitor performance on a held-out validation set (20% of our data) and save the model that achieves the best validation F1 score. This whole process takes about 90 minutes on an RTX 4050 GPU, with the Biological Process model taking longest because it has the most output terms.

The fifth and final stage is prediction generation for the test set. For each test protein, we load its embedding and feed it through each of our three trained models to get probability predictions for all GO terms. But we don't just output these raw probabilities - we apply an important post-processing step called hierarchy enforcement. Remember how GO terms form a hierarchy? Our predictions need to respect this structure. Specifically, if we predict a child term with high confidence, we must also predict all its parent terms with at least that same confidence. We do this through a bottom-up propagation: for each predicted term, we find all its ancestors in the GO graph and update their probabilities to be at least as high as the child's probability. This ensures our predictions are biologically consistent and don't violate the fundamental structure of the Gene Ontology. Finally, we filter the predictions to only include terms with confidence above 1% (to reduce noise and file size) and format everything into the submission file format that Kaggle expects.

