##  What the Neural Networks Actually Learned

To understand what our neural networks learned, it's helpful to think about what they're trying to do at a fundamental level. Each network is essentially learning a mapping from embedding space to function space. The embedding space is that 1,280-dimensional space where ESM2 places proteins - proteins with similar sequences and evolutionary histories are close together in this space. The function space is the set of GO terms we're trying to predict. The neural network learns which regions of embedding space correspond to which functions.

Let's think about a concrete example with the Molecular Function model. Imagine a protein kinase - these are enzymes that attach phosphate groups to other proteins. Kinases tend to have similar sequence patterns because they need similar catalytic mechanisms. When ESM2 processes different kinase sequences, it places them in a similar region of its 1,280-dimensional embedding space. During training, our neural network sees many examples of proteins from this region that are all labeled with kinase-related GO terms. The network learns that when the input embedding has certain patterns of values - perhaps high values in dimensions 45, 123, and 891 and low values in dimensions 27, 555, and 1043 - this strongly indicates kinase activity. It's learning feature combinations that are diagnostic for specific functions.

The first hidden layer of our network learns relatively simple combinations of input features. A neuron in this layer might fire strongly when dimensions 45 and 123 are both high, for example. The second hidden layer learns more complex combinations - a neuron here might respond to a specific pattern across multiple first-layer neurons. This hierarchical learning of increasingly complex features is what makes deep neural networks so powerful. By the time we reach the output layer, the network has transformed the input embedding into a representation where different regions clearly correspond to different functions.

It's important to understand that the network doesn't "understand" biology in any human sense. It doesn't know what a kinase is or why phosphorylation is important. Instead, it has learned statistical associations between embedding patterns and function labels. These associations work because the embeddings capture biologically meaningful information (thanks to ESM2's pre-training), and because evolution tends to conserve sequence patterns that are important for function. Proteins that do similar things have similar sequences because they evolved from common ancestors, and this evolutionary signal is what both ESM2 and our networks are picking up on.

The three networks - for Molecular Function, Biological Process, and Cellular Component - end up learning quite different things because these three ontologies capture fundamentally different aspects of protein biology. The Molecular Function model learns biochemical activity patterns. These tend to be relatively well-conserved in sequences because the catalytic mechanisms and binding sites must be preserved for the protein to work. The Cellular Component model learns localization signals. Many of these are explicit sequence motifs - for example, certain amino acid patterns signal "send this protein to the nucleus" or "embed this in the membrane." The Biological Process model has the hardest job because process participation is often context-dependent. A protein might participate in different processes depending on when it's expressed, what other proteins are around, or what cell type it's in. The sequence alone doesn't always contain enough information to reliably predict process participation, which is why our BPO model tends to have lower accuracy than the other two.

One fascinating aspect of what the networks learn is implicit knowledge about protein families and domains. Proteins are often made up of modular units called domains - relatively independent structural and functional units that can appear in different combinations across different proteins. ESM2's embeddings capture information about which domains are present in a protein, and our networks learn associations between certain domain patterns and certain functions. For example, if ESM2's embedding indicates the presence of both a kinase domain and a DNA-binding domain, the network learns to predict both kinase activity (Molecular Function) and transcription regulation (Biological Process). The network is essentially learning a complex, high-dimensional version of pattern matching: "if the embedding looks like pattern X, predict function Y."

